
:Selector
=========

Selector are patterns used to match, or select, the elements you want to style.

:hover
:active
:focus
:root
:nth_child

1. :hover
=========

:hover matches when the user interacts with an element with a pointing device, but dones't necessarily activate it. 
 It is generally triggered when the user hovers over an element with the cursor (mouse pointer)

 button:hover {
    background: red;
 }

 2. :active
 -----------
 active allows you to set styles for the element that is being interacted with right now. For example, you can give a button a style that will be visible in the brief moment when the mouse button is pressed.

 button {
    background_color: #bada55;
    transition:  backgound 0.3s, color o.3s;
 }

button:active {
    color: white;
    background-color: purple;
}

3. :focus
-----------

:focus represents an element (such as a form input) that has received focus. It is generally triggered when the user clicks or taps on an element
or selects it with the keyboard's Tab key.

button:focus {
   color: white;
   background-color: purple;
}

button {
   background-color: #bada55;
}

4. :root 
========
:root matches the root element of a tree representing the doucument. In HTML, :root represents the <html> element and is identical to the selector html,
except that is specifity is higher.

:root {
   --blue: #1e90ff;
   --white: #ffffff;
}
button {
   background-color: var(--blue);
}
h1 {
   color: var (--white);
}

5. :nth-child()

:nth-child() allows you to select elements based on their index (source order) inside their container.

div:nth-child(1) 
div:nth-child(odd) -- 1, 3, 5, 7
div:nth-child(event) -- 2, 4, 6, 8
